Where There’s Smoke, There Might Be Fire¶

Introduction¶

A smoke detector is an electronic device used to sense the presence of smoke, often sounding an alarm when it identifies a certain level of particle concentration in a room's air. These sensors play a pivotal role in detecting fires early and giving people the necessary time to evacuate and call for help. However, smoke detectors have a high false alarm rate, which can create a misleading sense of security and potentially compromise fire safety. Our goal is to train a model that helps to improve smoke detector accuracy by using this dataset to answer the following predictive question: can we use a sensor data from a smoke detector to accurately predict whether or not there is an active fire?

The dataset we'll be using contains nearly 60,000 observations from a "smart" smoke detector, which records measurements from many different sensors. These include measurements related to particle concentration and type, air-related parameters, and environmental parameters, which were observed both with and without an active fire nearby. Generally, air temperature (degrees Celsius) and humidity (percentage) are two of the most influential factors for a fire, so for this analysis we will only focus on these two variables.

First, we must download the dataset. Although we found it on Kaggle, it originates from an article by Stefan Blattmann; we will read the .csv file from his GitHub.

After reading the data, we select the columns that we will use (temp, humidity, and fire), and rename them to be easier to work with. In a similar vein, we replace the numerical "fire" variable with a factor: "Fire" if a fire has been detected in an observation, and "No Fire" otherwise.

Finally, we take 25% of our data as a training set and put aside the remainder for testing.

In [2]:
smoke_data <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Blatts01/ai-smokedetector/main/data/final.csv") |>
    rename_with(make.names) |> # Remove messy characters from column names
    select(Temperature.C., Humidity..., Fire.Alarm)

# Better column names
colnames(smoke_data) = c("temp", "humidity", "fire")   

smoke_data$fire[smoke_data$fire == 1] <- "Fire"
smoke_data$fire[smoke_data$fire == 0] <- "No Fire"
smoke_data <- mutate(smoke_data, fire = as_factor(fire))

# Split into training and testing data
smoke_split <- initial_split(smoke_data, prop = 0.25, strata = fire)
smoke_train <- training(smoke_split)
smoke_test <- testing(smoke_split)

To get a general idea of some of the properties of the data, we perform some preliminary data analysis.

Figure 1 illustrates the proportions of each class in the training data. There appears to be a slightly less than three times as many observations without fires compared to observations with fires. While this is not perfect, we believe that the data is not unbalanced enough to drastically harm our model.

We also calculate the mean, maximum, and minimum measurements of the two predictors, Temperature and Humidity (Figure 2). This reveals significant differences in scale between the two quantities and when we build our KNN model, we will need to center and scale our predictors.

Plotting temperature against humidity (Figure 3), we observe some general trends.

First, when both temperature and humidity are low, there are no fires. But when only one of the two quantities is high, fires are more common. However, when both temperature and humidity are moderately high, there is an area of overlap; it is unclear from the graph alone whether an observation in this region should have a fire or not.

We will train a k-nearest neighbours model to be able to quantitatively predict whether a reading represents an active fire.

We conduct five-fold cross-validation in order to determine the ideal number of neighbours for our model.

Since we have a large number of observations in our training set, we will perform two rounds of cross-validation: a rough first pass, with a few k values ranging from 1 to 501, and a finer pass on a smaller range of k that probably contains the best choice.

By looking at Figure 4, we can see that accuracy tends to decrease as k increases.

In [5]:
# knn model to determine best k
knn_spec_tune <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
    set_engine("kknn") |>
    set_mode("classification")

smoke_recipe <- recipe(fire ~ ., data = smoke_train) |>
    step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
    step_center(all_predictors())

smoke_vfold <- vfold_cv(smoke_train, v = 5, strata = fire)

k_vals_1 = tibble(neighbors = seq(from = 1, to = 501, by = 50)) # rough first pass

smoke_results_1 <- workflow() |>
    add_model(knn_spec_tune) |>
    add_recipe(smoke_recipe) |>
    tune_grid(resamples = smoke_vfold, grid = k_vals_1) |>
    collect_metrics()

k_vs_acc_1 <- smoke_results_1 |>
  filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = neighbors, y = mean)) +
  ggtitle("Figure 4: Accuracy vs. K") +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20)) +
  labs(x = "Neighbors", y = "Accuracy Estimate")
k_vs_acc_1

For our second round of cross-validation, we will test all k values between 1 and 60.

Figure 5 demonstrates that the ideal k is most likely 10, with an accuracy slightly above ~91%.

In [6]:
k_vals_2 = tibble(neighbors = 1:60) # fine-grained second pass

smoke_results_2 <- workflow() |>
  add_model(knn_spec_tune) |>
  add_recipe(smoke_recipe) |>
  tune_grid(resamples = smoke_vfold, grid = k_vals_2) |>
  collect_metrics()

k_vs_acc_2 <- smoke_results_2 |>
  filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = neighbors, y = mean)) +
  ggtitle("Figure 5: Accuracy vs. K") +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20)) +
  labs(x = "Neighbors", y = "Accuracy Estimate")
k_vs_acc_2

We sort by accuracy, select the best k, and use it to create a new model specification.

In [11]:
best_k <- smoke_results_2 |>
    filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
    arrange(desc(mean)) |>
    slice(1) |>
    pull(neighbors)

knn_spec_best <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = best_k) |>
  set_engine("kknn") |>
  set_mode("classification")

Results¶

Now that we have found the ideal number of neighbours, we can fit our model to the training set and use it to predict values from the testing set.

The final accuracy of the model is 91.57%.

By observing the confusion matrix (Figure 6), we can see that the model tends to mistakenly predict "Fire" (false positive) approximately twice as often as it mistakenly predicts "No Fire" (false negative).

In [8]:
smoke_fit <- workflow() |>
  add_recipe(smoke_recipe) |>
  add_model(knn_spec_best) |>
  fit(data = smoke_train)

smoke_predicted <- smoke_fit |>
  predict(smoke_test) |>
  bind_cols(smoke_test)

smoke_accuracy <- smoke_predicted |>
  metrics(truth = fire, estimate = .pred_class) |>
  filter(.metric == "accuracy") |>
  pull(.estimate)
smoke_accuracy

conf_mat <- smoke_predicted |>
    conf_mat(truth = fire, estimate = .pred_class)
conf_mat

Finally, we can visualize the outputs of our model for a range of inputs by creating a decision boundary plot (Figure 7).

This plot reinforces what we hypothesized in our preliminary analysis: when both humidity and temperature are either low or high, the chance of a fire is low. But when just one of the two variables is very high, or both variables are moderately high, there is likely an active fire.

# create the grid of temperature/humidity vals, and arrange in a data frame
temp_grid <- seq(min(smoke_data$temp), 
                max(smoke_data$temp), 
                length.out = 100)
humid_grid <- seq(min(smoke_data$humidity), 
                max(smoke_data$humidity), 
                length.out = 100)
asgrid <- as_tibble(expand.grid(temp = temp_grid, 
                                humidity = humid_grid))

# bind the predictions as a new column with the grid points
prediction_table <- predict(smoke_fit, asgrid) |> 
    bind_cols(asgrid)

Discussion¶

In this analysis, we created a model that could be used in order to detect active fires using a "smart" smoke detector. We identified air temperature and air humidity as potential predictors of fires, and used them to construct a k-nearest neighbours classifier. Several rounds of five-fold cross-validation were used to select the best value of k, which turned out to be k = 10.

Referring to the confusion matrix in Figure 6, we can calculate the final accuracy of the classifier:

$$\frac{32347+10667}{32347+2738+10667+1221} * 100\% = 91.57\%$$

Moreover, for the incorrect predictions that the model made, it generally predicted a false fire far more often than it neglected to trigger the alarm when there really was a fire (2738 vs. 1221 occurences). This is crucial as a "false negative" could lead to disastrous consequences.

Figure 7 is a decision boundary plot, which visualizes the predictions of the model on a continuum of inputs. Red represents a prediction of "No Fire" and blue represents a prediction "Fire".

As we can see, the blue area is concentrated in the bottom right of the graph, meaning that fires are predicted when there is both low temperature and high humidity. This is surprising, as intuitively one would think that fires are hot and dry. This might be a consequence of how our dataset was collected; observations were measured in very controlled environments, with fires much smaller than most housefires. Additionally, there is a small cluster of blue close to the top left of the graph, indicating a moderately high temperature and low humidity. This matches up with the predictions in our preliminary data analysis, and with our intuition that fires thrive in hot and dry environments.

This model is attempting to predict the presence of an active fire. Since a wrong prediction could potentially affect hundreds or thousands of lives, a high level of accuracy is mandatory. While 92% is a relatively good accuracy for a prediction model, it is unacceptably low in this context. We do not believe that this current model should be used to predict active fires, and improvements have to be made in order to increase its accuracy. For context, the accuracy of a typical multi-sensor smoke detector is between 94100% in various tests (To & Fong, 2017).

Although our model is not perfect, its relative simplicity means that should it be improved, it would likely be very cost-effective to implement. Unlike current smoke detectors, which use radiation and laser technologies to detect fires, our model only requires relatively simple temperature and humidity sensors (NIST, 2022). Making fire alarm systems more affordable and reliable would have a significant positive impact on the safety of lower-income households.

Finally, our analysis leads to several future questions. Most importantly, how can such a classification model be improved? One potential area of future research is using different combinations of predictors. Initially, we intended to use several variables from our dataset. However, due to the size of our dataset, this proved to be overwhelming for our limited computing resources. The data contains a rich variety of measurements, and using more of these could lead to a better model. Also, it may be that k-nearest neighbours is inadequate for this application; machine learning algorithms could be worth exploring.

Another future consideration is whether we need to upsample our training data. As shown in Figure 1, the training data has an approximately 3:1 ratio between "No Fire" and "Fire". As we deemed the dataset to be relatively balanced, we did not upsample the training data. Depending on the training data proportion in future analyses, it may be helpful to incorporate this practice into our data processing procedure.

Finally, there may be flaws or biases in the data itself. The active fires that were recorded by the author of the data were small and controlled, and could possibly differ in characteristics from the type of large, uncontrolled fires that smoke alarms aim to prevent. Future experiments should aim to replicate a house fire as closely as possible, and should attempt to control for external influences such as building materials and wind speed in order to create data that is representative of real emergencies.
